node.text: Americans are funding their retirement accounts at record rates. But figuring out how much your monthly contributions will be worth in a few decades can be confusing. As a rule of thumb, most financial advisors suggest that you save 10% to 15% of your salary. But if your goal is to get to $1 million, the percentage you need to invest will vary drastically based on how old you are when you start. Here's how you can make it happen.

node.title: How you can save $1 million making $35,000 per year, broken down by age

node.text: Investments in farmland are growing across the country as people, including the ultra-wealthy like Bill Gates, look for new ways to grow their money. In 2020, Gates made headlines for becoming the largest private farmland owner in the U.S. He had accumulated more than 269,000 acres of farmland across 18 states in less than a decade. His farmland grows onions, carrots and even the potatoes that are used to make McDonald’s french fries. How is he making money off of farmland in the U.S.? Watch the video to find out.

node.title: Why the ultra-wealthy like Bill Gates are investing in U.S. farmland

node.text: Porsche is in the minds of many the ultimate sports car brand. Its cars – especially its legendary 911 – blend high performance with quality construction and even a solid reputation for dependability. But the brand that made its name with small nimble two-door sports cars ruffled feathers in the automotive world when it tried its hand at a four-door sport utility vehicle, the Cayenne. Today, SUVs make up a huge chunk of Porsche’s sales. The brand is now entering the race toward electrification – but this time the innovator is playing catch-up to others.

node.title: How Porsche went from sports cars to SUVs ... and EVs

node.text: It’s taken over two years, but these days Jeremy Mateo is finally feeling at home. Mateo, 27, is a real estate broker in Honolulu, Hawaii, and bought his first condo on Oahu island right before the coronavirus pandemic in March 2020. Over the course of a year he saved $60,000 for a down payment and worked toward his goal of buying his “dream home.” Then he spent another year renovating and furnishing his place. The last of his furniture arrived in spring 2021, finally closing the chapter on his homebuying journey. Here’s how Mateo bought his one-bedroom condo for $560,000. (With @CNBCMakeIt)

node.text:
Airbnb is planning to start housing 20,000 Afghan refugees around the world free of charge, the company’s CEO, Brian Chesky, said Tuesday.⁠
⁠
The refugees will be housed in properties listed on Airbnb’s platform and the stays will be funded by Airbnb, Chesky said on Twitter, without specifying exactly how much the company plans to spend on the commitment or how long refugees will be housed for.⁠
⁠
Details on how many people the U.S. has evacuated from Afghanistan so far at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 23, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and text that says 'Venice set to introduce an entry fee and booking system for tourists CNBC'.

node.text:
Would you visit a city with an entrance fee?⁠
⁠
Venice is set to impose an entry fee for visitors in a bid to prevent huge crowds of tourists descending on the city.⁠
⁠
Italian newspaper La Stampa reported over the weekend that a package of measures designed to control tourism, which include requiring visitors to book in advance, pay a fee and enter the city via electronic turnstiles, is set to be imposed from summer 2022.⁠
⁠
How high could the entrance fee be? Find out at the link in bio.

node.text: Americans are funding their retirement accounts at record rates. But figuring out how much your monthly contributions will be worth in a few decades can be confusing. As a rule of thumb, most financial advisors suggest that you save 10% to 15% of your salary. But if your goal is to get to $1 million, the percentage you need to invest will vary drastically based on how old you are when you start. Here's how you can make it happen.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 23, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says '"The climate is f---ed." Chris Sacca CNBC'.

node.text:
Billionaire venture capitalist Chris Sacca has a message for anyone who will listen: “The climate is f---ed. Even worse than it seems,” he said in a 12-page letter to potential investors, obtained by Axios on Monday.⁠
⁠
Sacca’s climate-focused firm Lowercarbon Capital announced a new capital raise of $800 million on Thursday, which Sacca said will be used to “keep unf---ing the planet.” This is the first time the firm has accepted outside money, according to Crunchbase, and it comes on the heels of the earth’s hottest month on record: July 2021.⁠
⁠
Why does Sacca think addressing climate change should be good for a company’s bottom line? Find out at the link in bio. (With @CNBCMakeIt)

node.text:
It’s been a good few days for bitcoin investors.⁠
⁠
The digital token is trading at nearly $50,000, its highest point in months. And many people who’ve stayed on the sidelines are probably wondering yet again: Is it time to buy the cryptocurrency?⁠
⁠
Before you put your money into the still highly volatile asset, however, there are three helpful things to consider, according to financial and behavioral experts. Visit the link in bio to find out what those things are. 👀

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 23, 2021. May be an image of airplane and text that says 'Pentagon orders u.S. airlines to help fly Afghanistan evacuees CNBC'.

node.text:
The Pentagon has ordered U.S. commercial airlines to provide planes to help speed up Afghanistan evacuation efforts, it said Sunday.⁠
⁠
The planes would not fly into Kabul but instead would be used to transport those who have already been flown out of the country to military bases or transit points in Europe and the Middle East. That would allow military aircraft to focus on operations in and out of the Afghan capital, the Pentagon said.⁠
⁠
Details on how many people have been evacuated from the country since Aug. 14 at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 23, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'FDA grants full approval to Pfizer-BioNTech's Covid shot, clearing path to more vaccine mandates S CNBC'.

node.text:
The FDA grants Pfizer and BioNTech full U.S. approval of their Covid-19 vaccine.⁠
⁠
Until now, the mRNA vaccine was on the U.S. market under an Emergency Use Authorization, which was granted by the FDA in December. More than 204 million of the Pfizer shots have been administered, according to data compiled by the CDC.⁠
⁠
Read more at the link in bio.

node.text: Investments in farmland are growing across the country as people, including the ultra-wealthy like Bill Gates, look for new ways to grow their money. In 2020, Gates made headlines for becoming the largest private farmland owner in the U.S. He had accumulated more than 269,000 acres of farmland across 18 states in less than a decade. His farmland grows onions, carrots and even the potatoes that are used to make McDonald’s french fries. How is he making money off of farmland in the U.S.? Watch the video to find out.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 22, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'How much money a single person needs to earn to get by in every U.S. state AK Living Wage Minimum ($USD) 30000 35000 40000 WA MT ME ND MN WI VT ID NH MI WY SD IA NY OR IL MA NV IN RI co oH NE PA MO NJ CA KY CT UT WV NM VA KS MD AR DE TN AZ NC OK SC HI DC LA MS AL GA TX FL Source: MIT Living Wage Calculator CNBC'.

node.text:
For single people living in the U.S., earning enough money to make ends meet looks different for each person.⁠
⁠
But location can play a major role, since the cost of housing, food, insurance and other necessities varies from place to place. Overall, living costs have been increasing for Americans. They are spending more on where they live, the food they buy and how they get around, according to MIT’s Living Wage Calculator.⁠
⁠
What's considered a living wage for a single person in your state? Find out at the link in bio. (With @CNBCMakeIt)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 22, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'This is the one money bias that "hurts investors the most," says financial psychologist CNBC'.

node.text:
In investing, as in most walks of life, it pays to remember that childhood rhetorical question you’d get after going along with something stupid your friends were doing: “If your friends were jumping off a bridge, would you do it, too?”⁠
⁠
The desire to go along with what the group is doing, and the fear of what might happen if you don’t, is hard-wired into your brain, says one expert. But that need to keep up with the pack could hurt you financially in the long run. ⁠
⁠
Read about why you may well be susceptible to this dangerous financial bias, and what you can do to overcome it, at the link in bio. #investinyou (In partnership with @acorns)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 22, 2021. May be an image of 4 people and text that says 'This couple retired at 40 and moved their family to Portugal. Here's how they did it DTAVER 180074 OUR JOLRNEY RICH PARKER SMITH we are Financially Independent We RETIRED! CNBC'.

node.text:
From their home near Portugal, U.S. ex-pats Amon and Christina Browning give off the relaxed aura of a couple completely content with where they are in life. 😌⁠
⁠
And given they spend their days lounging on the beach or working in their garden, it’s not hard to see why. Now 41 and 43, the Brownings retired in 2019, when Amon was 39 and Christina was 41. ⁠
⁠
They were able to retire early by pursuing the financial independence, retire early, or FIRE, movement. Link in bio for details on how they made FIRE achievable on their salaries. (With @CNBCMakeIt)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 21, 2021. May be an image of one or more people, mountain and text that says 'The No. 1 reason people want to change careers is better work-life balance, survey finds CNBC'.

node.text:
When it comes to changing careers, pay isn’t the No. 1 motivator for Americans. ⁠
⁠
Instead, they want a better work-life balance, according to a survey by FlexJobs. ⁠
⁠
Meanwhile, more than 68% of U.S. workers polled said they would consider changing careers, and 19% said they would think about it if it was an amazing opportunity.⁠
⁠
If you are thinking about changing careers, visit the link in bio for five strategies that can help you.
